133
00:07:03,354 --> 00:07:05,354
I'm afraid I was surprised.

134
00:07:07,054 --> 00:07:10,854
Well, what do you say about my bear? Doesn't he look very natural?

135
00:07:11,654 --> 00:07:13,954
Oh, he looks terribly natural.

136
00:07:13,954 --> 00:07:17,854
I'm very happy. It was a pure coincidence that I discovered him.

137
00:07:17,854 --> 00:07:19,654
Let's see what the children will say.

138
00:07:19,654 --> 00:07:20,854
Oh, merciful woman!

139
00:07:20,854 --> 00:07:23,154
You can't do that! Clara is so sensitive!

140
00:07:23,154 --> 00:07:25,054
Where did she drive him?

141
00:07:25,054 --> 00:07:29,054
We were passing by a circus and she lent it to him.

142
00:07:29,054 --> 00:07:30,354
That looks like her.

143
00:07:30,382 --> 00:07:34,382
I won't forget the face of Mrs. Rottenmeier so quickly.

144
00:07:38,382 --> 00:07:42,382
Mrs. Sesemann, fair lady, think of your health.

145
00:07:43,382 --> 00:07:45,382
I'll take care of her.

146
00:07:49,382 --> 00:07:50,382
Come in.

147
00:07:53,382 --> 00:07:55,176
Oh, great mother!

148
00:07:55,176 --> 00:07:58,976
I hate you. I'm a big, evil bear.

149
00:08:00,176 --> 00:08:01,976
You'll taste good.

150
00:08:01,976 --> 00:08:03,976
Honey would taste much better for you.

151
00:08:03,976 --> 00:08:07,976
But you must have eaten honey for breakfast this morning.

152
00:08:08,976 --> 00:08:10,476
Dear grandmother.

153
00:08:11,176 --> 00:08:12,976
Did you at least get scared?

154
00:08:12,976 --> 00:08:15,976
No, not a little bit. I knew right away that it was you.

155
00:08:15,976 --> 00:08:17,976
You look funny.

156
00:08:17,976 --> 00:08:21,376
Funny? I look great here.

157
00:08:21,376 --> 00:08:22,376
Yes.

158
00:08:22,376 --> 00:08:23,376
Yes?

159
00:08:25,176 --> 00:08:25,710
Yes.

160
00:08:25,710 --> 00:08:29,210
You look good, Clara. Much better than I feared.

161
00:08:29,210 --> 00:08:31,210
I'm happy about it.

162
00:08:31,210 --> 00:08:33,210
It's good that you're here.

163
00:08:33,210 --> 00:08:35,210
Let me hug you, my child.

164
00:08:43,624 --> 00:08:46,624
Where is the little girl from Switzerland?

165
00:08:46,624 --> 00:08:50,624
What do you think, Clara, if we both surprise her with the bear costume?

166
00:08:50,624 --> 00:08:52,624
Oh yes!

167
00:08:52,624 --> 00:08:55,624
I'm sure I'm the first grandmother for her who looks like a bear.

168
00:08:55,624 --> 00:08:57,624
I'm curious what she says.

169
00:08:57,624 --> 00:08:59,624
And you have to hum loudly.

170
00:08:59,624 --> 00:09:02,624
You'll be surprised how beautifully I hum.

171
00:09:04,624 --> 00:09:08,624
No, not! You can't push the cart yourself!

172
00:09:08,624 --> 00:09:10,624
Sebastian, quick, Sebastian!

173
00:09:10,709 --> 00:09:14,209
Look, I'll take the cart for you, but I can do that myself.

174
00:09:14,209 --> 00:09:16,209
It's way too heavy for you.

175
00:09:17,209 --> 00:09:19,209
Poor lady, poor lady Moosmother.

176
00:09:40,709 --> 00:09:40,767
Subtitles by Stephanie Geiges

177
00:09:40,767 --> 00:09:43,767
You're hiding from me. That's how it is.

178
00:09:44,767 --> 00:09:46,767
I'm the big bear.

179
00:09:46,767 --> 00:09:48,767
Run away from me.

180
00:09:52,767 --> 00:09:54,767
Wait, I'll catch you.

181
00:09:55,767 --> 00:09:57,767
I'm faster than you.

182
00:09:57,767 --> 00:09:59,767
I like Swiss girls.

183
00:10:10,767 --> 00:10:13,767
I'm the big bear.

184
00:10:14,719 --> 00:10:16,719
I'm a big, evil bear!

185
00:10:16,719 --> 00:10:18,719
Not even Heidi is afraid!

186
00:10:20,719 --> 00:10:22,719
What? You're not afraid?

187
00:10:22,719 --> 00:10:24,719
And I tried so hard to scare you!

188
00:10:37,567 --> 00:10:39,567
Hello, dear grandmother.

189
00:10:39,567 --> 00:10:40,867
Hello, little Heidi.

190
00:10:40,867 --> 00:10:42,267
Adelheid, what's wrong with you?

191
00:10:42,267 --> 00:10:45,267
How many times do I have to tell you how you've grown up?

192
00:10:45,267 --> 00:10:48,267
Show me what I've taught you.

193
00:10:48,267 --> 00:10:51,267
It's not necessary. We've both already met.

194
00:10:51,267 --> 00:10:55,267
I practiced with Adelheid this morning and I want her to stick to it.

195
00:10:55,267 --> 00:10:59,567
I'm sorry I have to contradict you, but I can't give in on this point.

196
00:10:59,567 --> 00:11:02,767
I don't want to interfere with your education, of course.

197
00:11:02,767 --> 00:11:04,567
I'd be happy to.

198
00:11:04,567 --> 00:11:07,067
All right, Adelheid. Let's start over.

199
00:11:07,093 --> 00:11:13,093
How are you, Mrs. Gnädige?

200
00:11:13,093 --> 00:11:14,093
Mrs. Gnädige?

201
00:11:14,093 --> 00:11:19,093
All the trouble for free.

202
00:11:19,093 --> 00:11:22,093
Do you say Mrs. Gnädige at home in the mountains?

203
00:11:22,093 --> 00:11:24,093
No, of course not. Nobody says that.

204
00:11:24,093 --> 00:11:27,093
And neither do we. I've never heard it before.

205
00:11:27,093 --> 00:11:29,093
What is it, Adelheid? You know it.

206
00:11:29,093 --> 00:11:33,669
It's good. If you want, I'm the grandmother for you.

207
00:11:33,669 --> 00:11:36,669
But of course I want to, and I'd love to.

208
00:11:36,669 --> 00:11:40,669
And now it's your turn to introduce yourself. I have to know your name.

209
00:11:40,669 --> 00:11:43,669
My name is Heidi. But...

210
00:11:43,669 --> 00:11:45,669
maybe my name is Adelheid.

211
00:11:45,669 --> 00:11:48,669
Do you have two names? Or should I choose the one I like?

212
00:11:48,669 --> 00:11:51,669
I can explain that to you if you allow me.

213
00:11:51,669 --> 00:11:54,669
She calls herself Heidi. Her correct name is Adelheid.

214
00:11:54,669 --> 00:11:57,669
Oh, so that's how it is. She calls herself Heidi.

215
00:11:57,669 --> 00:12:00,669
Well, then she seems to be used to that name.

216
00:12:00,812 --> 00:12:02,812
Hello Heidi, how are you?

217
00:12:02,812 --> 00:12:04,812
Thank you, I'm very well.

218
00:12:12,918 --> 00:12:16,918
Mrs. Clara, I have to report that Mr. Candidate is waiting.

219
00:12:16,918 --> 00:12:18,918
Do we have to learn today, too?

220
00:12:18,918 --> 00:12:20,918
Why should we make an exception today?

221
00:12:20,918 --> 00:12:23,918
Because today is an exception. The grandmother came.

222
00:12:23,918 --> 00:12:26,918
And this grandmother doesn't run away that fast.

223
00:12:26,918 --> 00:12:28,918
I'd like to take part in the class.

224
00:12:28,918 --> 00:12:31,918
I'd like to see what progress has been made.

225
00:12:31,918 --> 00:12:34,918
You have nothing against it, Mrs. Rottenmeier.

226
00:12:34,918 --> 00:12:36,908
What? Why? Why? Why?

227
00:12:36,908 --> 00:12:41,408
Sebastian, please give the Bärenfeld to Johann. He should return it to the
circus.

228
00:12:41,408 --> 00:12:43,408
Yes, dear lady.

229
00:12:44,408 --> 00:12:46,408
Come in.

230
00:12:46,408 --> 00:12:48,408
Good day.

231
00:12:49,408 --> 00:12:55,408
Oh, what a pleasant surprise to be able to welcome you here again, Mrs.
Sesemann.

232
00:12:58,408 --> 00:13:04,300
You were no longer three, or no, two, maybe just one year no longer here.

233
00:13:04,300 --> 00:13:07,740
Yes, yes, that's how you notice how time goes by, you don't get any younger.

234
00:13:07,740 --> 00:13:10,060
The eyes don't want to be like that anymore, and the legs don't want to...

235
00:13:10,060 --> 00:13:11,420
That's good, Mr. Candidate.

236
00:13:11,420 --> 00:13:16,060
We can chat a little later, now we just want to start with the lesson.

237
00:13:16,060 --> 00:13:18,060
Yes, yes, I understand.

238
00:13:18,060 --> 00:13:22,380
Adelheid, please tell us the alphabet, we also want to show Mrs. Sesemann what
you learned here.

239
00:13:22,380 --> 00:13:30,780
A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H, I, uh, and then...

240
00:13:30,780 --> 00:13:33,980
A, B, C, D, E...

241
00:13:34,012 --> 00:13:50,572
...F, G, and H, I, J, K, L, M, N, O, P, Q, S, T, U, V, W, X, Y, and Z.

242
00:13:54,172 --> 00:13:55,772
And once again.

243
00:13:56,252 --> 00:14:00,332
A, B, C, D, E, F...

244
00:14:00,412 --> 00:14:24,412
G, H, I, J, K, L, M, N, O, P, Q, L, S, T, U, V, X, Y, Z, A, B, C, D, E, F, G,
H...

