249
00:14:45,510 --> 00:14:50,510
What I wanted to ask is, are you still that bad or do you have more appetite,
Clara?

250
00:14:52,510 --> 00:14:55,510
But how are you supposed to get big and strong if you don't want to eat?

251
00:14:55,510 --> 00:14:58,510
I don't like eating. I find eating terribly boring.

252
00:14:58,510 --> 00:14:59,508
What is it?

253
00:14:59,508 --> 00:15:02,708
Since when is eating boring? It always tastes good to me.

254
00:15:02,708 --> 00:15:07,708
I think it's nice to sit at the table, especially when there's something on the
plate that I like.

255
00:15:10,708 --> 00:15:13,708
What do you think you can do with plates?

256
00:15:13,708 --> 00:15:17,708
If they're really blank, you can sometimes even look into them.

257
00:15:20,708 --> 00:15:24,708
You can also fill the plate with water and let little ships swim on it.

258
00:15:24,708 --> 00:15:27,708
And you can even conjure with very deep plates.

259
00:15:27,708 --> 00:15:28,851
Conjure?

260
00:15:28,851 --> 00:15:30,151
Conjure?

261
00:15:30,151 --> 00:15:31,151
Sebastian?

262
00:15:31,151 --> 00:15:32,651
Yes, what do you want?

263
00:15:32,651 --> 00:15:35,651
Please be so kind and get me an even deeper plate.

264
00:15:35,651 --> 00:15:37,651
These are the deepest plates we have.

265
00:15:37,651 --> 00:15:40,151
Then get me glasses. Glasses work too.

266
00:15:40,151 --> 00:15:43,651
Glasses, yes. I will hurry, dear lady.

267
00:15:49,869 --> 00:15:51,869
I brought some water.

268
00:15:51,869 --> 00:15:53,869
That's good, Sebastian.

269
00:15:53,869 --> 00:15:57,869
I think these glasses are real magic glasses.

270
00:16:07,661 --> 00:16:10,661
What are you doing with that, Grandmother Waste?

271
00:16:10,661 --> 00:16:13,661
Just patience. You'll see.

272
00:16:26,861 --> 00:16:29,361
Oh, a colorful flower!

273
00:16:30,661 --> 00:16:32,661
You can do magic, Grandmother.

274
00:16:33,861 --> 00:16:36,861
But that's not all you can do with glasses.

275
00:16:36,861 --> 00:16:38,361
Just wait a moment.

276
00:16:44,397 --> 00:16:47,397
This seems to be a bit hoarse.

277
00:16:53,397 --> 00:16:54,381
Oh, the ringtone!

278
00:16:54,381 --> 00:16:56,381
You can make music!

279
00:16:59,381 --> 00:17:00,381
Well?

280
00:17:08,381 --> 00:17:09,381
That's...

281
00:17:09,517 --> 00:17:11,517
It's the melody by Henzinglein.

282
00:17:11,517 --> 00:17:14,517
If you've recognized it, then you can play it with me.

283
00:17:14,517 --> 00:17:16,517
Gladly. But with what?

284
00:17:16,517 --> 00:17:19,517
There will probably be more glasses.

285
00:17:19,517 --> 00:17:21,517
Sebastian, are there still a few glasses in the house?

286
00:17:29,869 --> 00:17:33,869
Well, let's give it a try together. One, two...

287
00:17:35,617 --> 00:17:36,617
Beautiful!

288
00:17:55,617 --> 00:17:56,617
Good!

289
00:18:04,617 --> 00:18:04,740
Subtitles by Stephanie Geiges

290
00:18:04,740 --> 00:18:08,740
Subtitles by Stephanie Geiges

291
00:18:13,188 --> 00:18:17,188
Since when do you stand on the chair? Do you only have nonsense in your head?

292
00:18:17,188 --> 00:18:19,188
Listen to this, Mrs. Rottenmeier.

293
00:18:19,188 --> 00:18:22,188
I happened to have the nonsense in my head.

294
00:18:22,188 --> 00:18:25,188
Mrs. Seselmann, that can't be true.

295
00:18:25,188 --> 00:18:27,188
Oh yes, Mrs. Rottenmeier, that can be true.

296
00:18:27,188 --> 00:18:33,188
And you can't even imagine what fun it is to make music with a simple spoon and
glasses.

297
00:18:43,188 --> 00:18:45,188
Stop it! Right now!

298
00:18:45,540 --> 00:18:47,540
I don't want to listen to music.

299
00:18:47,540 --> 00:18:49,540
I'll listen if I want to.

300
00:18:49,540 --> 00:18:52,540
It's time for dinner. It's seven o'clock.

301
00:18:52,540 --> 00:18:55,540
If that's the case, we really have to stop now.

302
00:18:55,540 --> 00:18:58,540
I'm almost starved anyway.

303
00:19:02,540 --> 00:19:07,434
It's nice with your grandmother. You were right, Clara. She's really very nice.

304
00:19:07,434 --> 00:19:11,434
I like her very, very much. She's always like that. She always comes up with
something funny.

305
00:19:11,434 --> 00:19:14,434
I envy you. You have the best grandmother in the world.

306
00:19:14,434 --> 00:19:15,434
She's yours now.

307
00:19:15,434 --> 00:19:20,434
Do you know what I noticed? You haven't thought about the mountains today.

308
00:19:21,434 --> 00:19:24,434
Yes, that's right. Why do you know that?

309
00:19:24,434 --> 00:19:27,434
I read it from your face.

310
00:19:28,434 --> 00:19:30,434
There are letters on it.

311
00:19:30,434 --> 00:19:32,434
So, Clara!

312
00:19:36,106 --> 00:19:41,106
Go to your room, Heidi. Otherwise Mrs. Rottenmeier will find you here and curse
at you again.

313
00:19:42,106 --> 00:19:46,106
Adelaide, what are you doing in Mrs. Clara's room? Get out!

314
00:19:49,106 --> 00:19:50,106
Good night, Clara.

315
00:19:51,106 --> 00:19:52,106
Good night, Heidi.

316
00:19:58,052 --> 00:19:59,852
But, but, that's not possible.

317
00:19:59,852 --> 00:20:01,352
Do you think I'm lying to you?

318
00:20:01,352 --> 00:20:03,052
No, no, of course not.

319
00:20:03,052 --> 00:20:04,752
Then go and do what I tell you.

320
00:20:04,752 --> 00:20:07,252
Mrs. Sesemann won't stay long, she's leaving soon.

321
00:20:07,252 --> 00:20:09,052
Yes, very well, I understand.

322
00:20:09,052 --> 00:20:10,052
It will be done.

323
00:20:21,852 --> 00:20:25,252
La, la, la, la, la, la.

324
00:20:25,252 --> 00:20:29,252
La la la la la la la la.

325
00:20:30,252 --> 00:20:33,252
The grandmother is really very funny.

326
00:20:38,252 --> 00:20:39,252
Who's there?

327
00:20:39,252 --> 00:20:40,252
It's me.

328
00:20:40,252 --> 00:20:41,252
Pssst!

329
00:20:44,964 --> 00:20:46,964
Hello, Grandmother.

330
00:20:46,964 --> 00:20:48,964
Can I come in?

331
00:20:48,964 --> 00:20:49,964
Of course.

332
00:20:49,964 --> 00:20:53,964
We have to be quiet, otherwise Mrs. Rottenmeier will hear us and will scold us
again.

333
00:20:53,964 --> 00:20:55,964
Tell me, why haven't you gone to sleep yet?

334
00:20:55,964 --> 00:20:57,964
Can you fall asleep already?

335
00:20:57,964 --> 00:20:58,964
No.

336
00:20:58,964 --> 00:21:01,964
I have something for you that I wanted to give you.

337
00:21:01,964 --> 00:21:03,964
A present?

338
00:21:03,964 --> 00:21:05,964
This one.

339
00:21:07,964 --> 00:21:08,964
Don't you like it?

340
00:21:08,964 --> 00:21:10,881
Yes, I even like it very much.

341
00:21:10,881 --> 00:21:12,481
But I can't read it yet.

342
00:21:12,481 --> 00:21:15,181
That's not a problem. There are some nice pictures to look at.

343
00:21:15,181 --> 00:21:16,681
Take a look.

344
00:21:16,681 --> 00:21:19,481
Maybe you'll learn how to read with this book.

345
00:21:19,481 --> 00:21:22,481
It's not as hard as you think it is.

346
00:21:25,481 --> 00:21:27,081
Should I read you some of it?

347
00:21:27,081 --> 00:21:27,881
Oh, yes.

348
00:21:27,881 --> 00:21:29,781
Then hurry up and go to bed, Heidi.

349
00:21:29,781 --> 00:21:32,481
I'll read you so long until your eyes close.

350
00:21:32,481 --> 00:21:34,081
Hooray!

351
00:21:37,181 --> 00:21:39,281
I'm done.

352
00:21:39,345 --> 00:21:41,345
You, grandmother?

353
00:21:41,345 --> 00:21:42,345
What is it, my child?

354
00:21:42,345 --> 00:21:45,345
Miss Rottenmeier says you're leaving soon.

355
00:21:45,345 --> 00:21:47,345
Does she say that?

356
00:21:47,345 --> 00:21:50,345
Yes, she said it to Sebastian this evening.

357
00:21:50,345 --> 00:21:54,345
I'm still here and I don't plan to leave so soon.

358
00:21:54,345 --> 00:21:56,345
Ah, that's nice.

359
00:21:56,345 --> 00:21:58,345
Are you ready? Can I start?

360
00:21:58,345 --> 00:21:59,345
Yes.

361
00:22:00,345 --> 00:22:06,345
Once upon a time in a distant land, far behind the seven mountains,

362
00:22:06,345 --> 00:22:08,065
there lived a little girl.

363
00:22:08,065 --> 00:22:12,565
Grandmother read and read, and Heidi listened attentively.

364
00:22:12,565 --> 00:22:15,565
Grandmother had to read three long fairy tales,

365
00:22:15,565 --> 00:22:20,565
until Heidi could no longer keep her eyes open and fell asleep.

366
00:22:20,565 --> 00:22:22,565
Finally!

367
00:22:38,065 --> 00:22:41,065
Subtitles by Stephanie Geiges

368
00:22:50,459 --> 00:22:56,459
Heidi had been loved by her grandmother from the bottom of her heart, and Mrs.
Sesermann also liked the little girl.

369
00:22:56,459 --> 00:23:00,459
She spent a lot of time teaching Heidi how to read and write.

370
00:23:00,459 --> 00:23:07,459
And then one day, by chance, she came to the secret of why Heidi was sometimes
so sad.

371
00:23:07,459 --> 00:23:11,459
She understood that Heidi was having a heart attack.

372
00:23:11,459 --> 00:23:18,459
To make Klara happy and to comfort Heidi, she thought it would be a surprise for
the children.

373
00:23:18,785 --> 00:23:27,285
She went with them on a warm spring day out to the country, but we want to tell
you about that in our next story.

374
00:23:48,785 --> 00:23:50,785
To be continued

